Date: Sun 27 Nov 2005
From: Badri Badrinath <badrishanthi@hotmail.com>
Source: Daily Times Monitor (Pakistan), Sat 26 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2005%5C11%5C26%5Cstory_26-11-2005_pg1_4>

Pakistan: Over 40 Diagnosed with Hemorrhagic Fever
-----------------------------------------------
More than 40 people have been diagnosed with hemorrhagic fever and are
being treated in Karachi, a top health official in the Sindh government
told news agencies on Fri 25 Nov 2005.
Hospitals were on alert after the fever was confirmed to have killed 5
people, including a woman doctor, in the last 6 weeks, health officials
said. Doctors in Karachi have been ordered to take special protective
measures, as the disease can spread by massive bleeding, with which
patients with the fever suffer, he said. "All hospitals were put on high
alert after 5 people died of hemorrhagic fever, and there are over 40 under
treatment," Sindh Health Secretary Naushad Sheikh said.
At least 39 patients have been admitted to the Aga Khan Hospital and 5 to
government hospitals. All 5 of the latest deaths were confirmed on Friday
[25 Nov 2005] as cases of viral hemorrhagic fever, Sheikh said. 28 of the
41 have recovered and have been discharged, Dr. Afia said. She said 7
suspected patients have been confirmed as suffering from dengue fever,
while one was suffering from Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever (CCHF). "Their
status was lab-confirmed," she said. Zafar said that 34 patients were from
Karachi, 4 from Jacobabad, 3 from Hyderabad, 2 from Balochistan and one
from Larkana.
Pakistan has suffered many cases of CCHF. An outbreak in 2004 claimed 3
lives in Balochistan.
The female doctor, who has died, was admitted to AKUH bleeding profusely
from her mouth, ears and nose.
Meanwhile, Sindh Health Minister Shabbir Qaimkhani has said that all
preventive measures have been taken against viral hemorrhagic fever, CCHF
and bird flu virus. Hospital sources said [that the female doctor and
another doctor] had died and that there are unconfirmed reports that
another AKUH doctor has fallen sick. "We have one confirmed CCHF patient
and 7 or 8 dengue fever patients," said the AKUH sources. "The patients are
not arriving in clusters from one part of Karachi, but from all over the
city," said a doctor. "And their mortality is not that high." However, the
doctor said that there were chances of an epidemic if the government did
not spread awareness.
Naushad Sheikh said that the government is taking action. "9 of our
peripheral hospitals in the city have been directed to take precautions if
any [hemorrhagic fever] patient arrives and to immediately refer them to
JPMC, CHK or Lyari General Hospital," he said. "We will start spreading
awareness (about the virus) through television beginning on Friday [2 Dec
2005]."
--
Dr. P. Badrinath MD, BS, M. Phil, MPH, PhD (Cantab), MFPH
Consultant in Public Health & Affiliated Clinical Lecturer
Suffolk West PCT & University of Cambridge, UK
