Date: Sun 27 Nov 2005
From: Badri Badrinath <badrishanthi@hotmail.com>
Source: Daily Times Monitor (Pakistan), Sun 27 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2005\11\27\story_27-11-2005_pg7_7>

Pakistan: Hemorrhagic Fever Emergency Declared in Karachi
-----------------------------------------------
An emergency has been declared in Karachi's hospitals, where more than 50
patients suffering from hemorrhagic fever have been admitted.
Geo Television quoted the Sindh Health Department as saying on Sat 26 Nov
2005 that the deadly virus [Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever virus (CCHFV)]
has already claimed 5 lives -- including 2 doctors -- in the last 6 weeks.
Provincial Health Secretary Dr. Noshad Sheikh said that an emergency had
been declared in all hospitals of Karachi. The doctors treating patients
suffering from the fever have been directed to take precautionary measures,
Geo Television said. 50 patients, including 25 children, suffering from the
fever have been admitted to the Aga Khan Hospital, 5 to the Jinnah Hospital
and 3 to the Karachi Civil Hospital, Geo Television reported. All patients
are being kept in isolation wards.
Of the patients, 34 are residents of Karachi, 4 are from Jacobabad, 3 from
Hyderabad, 2 from Balochistan and one from Larkana, the television channel
reported.
Karachi Civil Hospital Medical Superintendent Dr. Kaleem Butt told Tanveer
Sher of Daily Times that the patients in his hospital are: a resident of
Karachi's Haji Camp, a resident of Thattha, and a 13-year-old from Jehangir
Road. He said that all 3 had been suffering for the last week from
high-grade fever, which could not be controlled by local doctors. When they
started bleeding from the nose and mouth, their families rushed them to
Civil Hospital, he said.
Butt said that their symptoms indicate that they are suffering from either
CCHV infection or another type of hemorrhagic fever. All 3 patients have
been administered anti-viral treatment and antibiotics, which have helped
stabilize their condition. Their blood samples have been sent to the Aga
Khan University (AKU) Laboratory, and the results are expected by Saturday
[3 Dec 2005] night.
The medical superintendent said that the new ward's capacity will be
enhanced from 10 to 35 beds soon, and a larger staff will be sent to the
isolation ward in 3 shifts from Saturday [3 Dec 2006?]. He said that the
hospital administration has acquired masks, suction machines, oxygen
cylinders, caps and gloves to protect their staff, while extensive
antiseptic spraying has also been carried out.
Karachi's hospitals have so far discharged 28 hemorrhagic fever patients
after their recovery.
--
Dr. P. Badrinath MD, BS, M. Phil, MPH, PhD (Cantab), MFPH
Consultant in Public Health & Affiliated Clinical Lecturer,
Suffolk West PCT & University of Cambridge, UK
<badrishanthi@hotmail.com>
[This outbreak of hemorrhagic fever appears to have multiple causes as, so
far, a laboratory-confirmed diagnosis had been established for no more than
9 of the more than 50 patients. Of these 9, 8 were diagnosed as dengue
fever cases and only one as CCHF. Furthermore, the patients were arriving
from different parts of the city, and, so far, there was no discernable
focus of infection as might have been expected in the case of CCHF [but
there are 40 more cases to be lab diagnosed. - Mod.JW]
[It is not clear from these accounts and the preceding account whether the
deceased female doctor contracted infection from hospitalized patients or
in the community. The circumstances surrounding the death of the 2nd doctor
are not revealed. - Mod.CP]
[CCHF is transmitted by ticks, and also by the blood of infected livestock
that have been butchered or prepared in the kitchen, and by infected fluids
from patients. I have never heard of dengue hemorrhagic fever being
transmitted to attending clinicians, so at least the doctors' deaths are
likely to have been due to CCHF. - Mod.JW]
